g.text: Pain Threshold: You can take this one too. Just breathe in slowly.
Pain Threshold: This is bad. Feels like sharp stones grinding in your chest and keeping you from moving.
Ceiling Fan: Still ongoing. Now is a good time to start worrying.
Ceiling Fan: Finally the stabbing recedes. You could try doing it again to see how painful it gets -- but you would probably die.
Pain Threshold: You can take it. Just breathe.
Pain Threshold: Finally the stabbing recedes. You could try doing it again to see how painful it gets. (Very.) But do you really want to risk it?
Endurance: Do it -- *if you want to die*, the stabbing pain in your chest is telling you. You're hanging by a thread here...
Ceiling Fan: The lights are off.
Pain Threshold: Still ongoing. Now is a good time to start worrying.
Ceiling Fan: The lights are off again.
You: Pull on the light bulb.
Ceiling Fan: The lights are on.
Ceiling Fan: Finally the pressure recedes. You find yourself covered in cold sweat and trying not to move -- hoping it will keep you from dying.
Ceiling Fan: It's even worse this time. Maybe you should stop trying to catch the tie?
Savoir Faire: You reach out to grab the tie... but what's this? Radiating chest pain! Fear washes over you.
Pain Threshold: You can take it. Just breathe in slowly.
Ceiling Fan: This is bad. Feels like sharp stones grinding in your chest and keeping you from moving.
Ceiling Fan: For quite a long time.
Ceiling Fan: This fan has two chain pull switches -- one ends in a tiny fan, the other in a light bulb. A truly horrific necktie has somehow attached itself to one of the blades.
Pain Threshold: Little black spots dance on your retinas. It's almost pleasurable.

Inland Empire: Or has it been consigned there as punishment? You feel as though this creature is your *friend* and wants to reattach itself to your neck. So that you may continue your adventures together in this strange world!
Pain Threshold: Your eyes burn with photosensitivity. It's not good.
Ceiling Fan: The blades come squeaking to a halt. It should be easier to reach the tie now.
The blades come squeaking to a halt.
Inland Empire: An ominous, foreboding feeling fills you, as you look at the tie.
Savoir Faire: Oh no, it's happening again. You didn't catch it and now there's numbness in half your chest.
You: Breathe in and out calmly.
Pain Threshold: This isn't a real heart attack. You should probably just exercise more.
Pain Threshold: Still bad. Definitely worse than the last time.
You: Press your hands to your chest to make sure your heart is still beating okay.
Savoir Faire: Oh no, it's happening again. You didn't catch it and now there's numbness in your left arm, plus half your chest.
Pain Threshold: You can take this. It's not nearly as bad as the last time.
Savoir Faire: You reach out to grab the tie... but what's this? Diffuse, radiating chest pain! Doom comes over you.
Ceiling Fan: This is not a *real* heart attack. This is a joke. It's probably just your lungs or your oesophagus. The oesophagus does practically nothing.
Ceiling Fan: The switch must be broken, because nothing happens. The air in the room is starting to feel like vaporized urine.
Pain Threshold: Finally the pressure recedes. You find yourself covered in cold sweat. Try not to move too fast -- maybe that will keep you from collapsing.
Ceiling Fan: What you have in your hand is a fantastically colourful tie, with four or five different patterns. The knot reminds you of a noose.
Logic: If it's your *friend*, why was it up there? Who ties their friend to a ceiling fan? Maybe this thing is dangerous somehow...
Ceiling Fan: The fan is spinning.
Ceiling Fan: None of these is a real heart attack. This is such a joke. You should probably just exercise more.
Pain Threshold: This is not a *real* heart attack. This is a joke. It's probably just your lungs or your oesophagus. The oesophagus does practically nothing.
Savoir Faire: You swoop up and catch the tie... Snap! It's released from the blade.
You swoop up and catch the tie... snap! It's released from the blade. WARNING! WARNING! The necktie is no longer contained.
Pain Threshold: It's just a little hangover-induced photosensitivity. Don't over-react.
You: Pull again to turn the lights off.
Pain Threshold: It's worse this time. Maybe you should stop trying to catch the tie?
Pain Threshold: For quite a long time.
Ceiling Fan: Still happening. Definitely worse than the last time.
Interfacing: You know what you should do? You should stop the fan and then try again, it'll get easier.
Ceiling Fan: A terrible mistake! Turn the lights off IMMEDIATELY! You can practically feel the photons burning a hole in your brain.
Ceiling Fan: What you have in your hand is a truly hideous necktie, with four or five different patterns. The knot reminds you of a noose.
